				</span>

			</td>
			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Typically you want to use UDP as your method for sending packets for these reasons...<br /><br /><br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://gafferongames.com/networking-for-game-programmers/udp-vs-tcp/">http://gafferongames.com/networking-for ... dp-vs-tcp/</a><!-- m --><br /><br /><br />Also most NES games aren't set up to take advantage of prediction since re-emulating the frame really isn't an option in a some games. Especially if more than a few frames have gone by. <br /><br /><br />The basic structure is<br /><br />1.  Determine number of frames to delay input (typically half the ping rounded up to the nearest integer or +1 frame for margin) on local machine by measuring average ping time over a time interval.<br />2.  Synchronize emulator startup/loading of rom<br />3.  Ignore first X frames  where X = frame delay since you can't possibly have any input from the other player.  <br />4.  Send input every frame with the frame it is to execute on. Frame to execute = current frame + delay<br />5.  Save own input to buffer for local machine<br />6.  On current frame check get own input from buffer and check to make sure input from other player has arrived. If it hasn't arrived emulation freezes until it does</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

